{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640471"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:16:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:16:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17827"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17827"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.04,0,0.84,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10541"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75179"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10541"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17827"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60687"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5688"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24585"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25029"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26003"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75179"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA non-competent child is one who lacks sufficient understanding and intelligence to enable them to fully understand what is proposed regarding their medical care.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the legal position regarding medical decision-making for a non-competent child?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Parents have absolute authority to refuse any treatment","Children under 16 years cannot consent to any treatment","Medical professionals can override all parental decisions","Parents must make decisions in the child\u0027s best interests","Decisions must wait until the child becomes competent"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that \u003Cstrong\u003Eparents must make decisions in the child\u0027s best interests\u003C/strong\u003E. While parents have the legal authority to make medical decisions for their non-competent children, this authority is not absolute and must be exercised in a way that promotes the child\u0027s welfare.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParents have absolute authority to refuse any treatment\u003C/strong\u003E - Parental authority is not absolute, as courts can intervene when decisions are deemed contrary to the child\u0027s best interests.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChildren under 16 years cannot consent to any treatment\u003C/strong\u003E - Some children under 16 may demonstrate sufficient maturity and understanding to make specific healthcare decisions, as recognised under Gillick competence.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedical professionals can override all parental decisions\u003C/strong\u003E - Healthcare providers must work with parents and can only challenge decisions through appropriate legal channels if concerned about the child\u0027s welfare.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecisions must wait until the child becomes competent\u003C/strong\u003E - Necessary medical care cannot be delayed when treatment is required, as this could harm the child\u0027s health outcomes.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe principle of acting in the child\u0027s best interests ensures that decisions about medical care prioritise the child\u0027s health and wellbeing while respecting the role of parents as primary decision-makers.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A non-competent child lacks the capacity to make informed decisions about their medical care.","Parents or legal guardians have the authority to make medical decisions on behalf of non-competent children.","Medical decisions for non-competent children must be made in the child\u0027s best interests."],"references":["Mandal J, Ponnambath DK, Parija SC. Bioethics: A brief review. Trop Parasitol. 2017;7(1):5-7. doi:10.4103/tp.TP_4_17","Varkey B. Principles of Clinical Ethics and Their Application to Practice. Med Princ Pract. 2021;30(1):17-28. doi:10.1159/000509119","Bradfield O. Children: Custody, competence and consent. Aust J Gen Pract. 2023; 12:832-35."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60687"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17827"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60687"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T09:34:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-29T09:35:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10541"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75179"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCoun